\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
We will use a discretised model or a system of magnetic dipoles (which may
 be elements of a discrete dipole approximation).
 The column vector he ∈ C2J contians the complex amplitudes of the cartesian
 field components of the external field at the position of the dipoles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Non-interacting case
\series default
: For a collection of non-interacting dipoles, it is found that:where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{\chi}}}(\boldsymbol{r})=\sum_{j}\frac{\gamma_{j}\mu_{0}m_{j}^{s}\omega}{(\omega_{0j}^{2}-\omega^{2})-i\omega\Gamma_{j}}\overline{\overline{\textrm{\boldsymbol{S}}}}_{j}\delta(\boldsymbol{r-\boldsymbol{r_{0j}}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{\textrm{S}}}}_{j}=\frac{\omega_{0j}}{\omega}\boldsymbol{\hat{i}\hat{i}}-i\boldsymbol{\hat{j}\hat{i}}+i\boldsymbol{\hat{i}\hat{j}}+\frac{\omega_{0j}}{\omega}\boldsymbol{\hat{j}\hat{j}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is the spin dyadic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we expand in the basis of he, χ becomes a block diagonal matrix.
 This represents the system in the non-interacting case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
2.
 Self interacting case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exchange interactions are added using another matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle G^{x}}$
\end_inset

- in the case of nearest neighbour interactions, simply the sum over local
 dipole moments (represented in the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{C}^{2J}$
\end_inset

 ).
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\textstyle m}=\chi{\textstyle h^{e}}+\chi{\textstyle G^{x}m}=(\chi^{-1}-{\textstyle G^{x}})^{-1}{\textstyle h^{e}}=\xi{\textstyle h^{e}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.
 Case with Scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scattered magnetic dipole field is calculated using the discretised
 Green's function, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle G^{d}}$
\end_inset

 using the magnetostatic Green's dyadic:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{G}}}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r'})=\frac{1}{|\boldsymbol{r}-\boldsymbol{r'}|^{3}}[\,3\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{R}}}(\boldsymbol{r},\boldsymbol{r'})-\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{I}}}\,]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the total field at the dipoles is thus given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h^{t}=h^{e}+G^{d}m=(I-G^{d}\xi)^{-1}h^{e}=\kappa h^{e}
\]

\end_inset

where we have used this to define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\xi\kappa h^{e}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Response Matricies of systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now define the three response matricies for the increasingly complex
 systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=\frac{\omega}{2}\mu_{0}\chi^{R}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\frac{\omega}{2}\mu_{0}\xi^{R}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{\omega}{2}\mu_{0}\kappa^{\dag}\xi^{R}\kappa
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{R},\xi^{R}$
\end_inset

are the hermitian parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $-i\chi,-i\xi$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 These give the absorbed power for the systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<P>=\textrm{Tr}\left[H^{e}N\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<P>=\textrm{Tr}\left[H^{e}M\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<P>=\textrm{Tr}\left[H^{e}L\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{e}$
\end_inset

 is the ensemble average over the outer product 
\begin_inset Formula $<h^{e}h^{e*}>$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hello
\end_layout

\end_body
